0_10	0.0	The bank is foreclosing on her landlord.
0_11	0.0	So Mendez -- a 34-year-old salon assistant -- has been trying to find a three-bedroom apartment for herself and her five children for more than three months.
0_12	0.0	She is having trouble finding anything for less than $800 per month in the same neighborhood as her children's schools.
0_13	0.0	''It's upsetting to those of us who've always worked and lived here in the city -- who have an education, who work hard and who still can't get what we want,'' said Mendez, who paid $350 a month for her top-floor apartment that she figures could now rent for $1,000 a month if it's rehabbed.
0_14	0.0	That's more than she makes in a month.
0_15	0.0	It's not that gentrification is a new concept.
0_16	0.0	But statistics show that it is an accelerating one.
0_17	0.0	Consider San Francisco's Mission District, a working-class, predominately Hispanic neighborhood that is quickly turning upscale.
0_18	0.0	In New York, old tenement buildings on Manhattan's Lower East Side are being converted into luxury units.
0_19	0.25	HUD researchers have found that the nation is losing low-income housing units at an increasingly alarming rate -- 400,000 units between 1993 and 1997, compared with 425,000 between 1985 and 1993.
0_20	0.0	Officials at Harvard University's Joint Center for Housing Studies also have noted the trend -- one that residents in some neighborhoods are trying to buck.
