3_0	0.0	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Judd Levy retired as Merrill Lynch's head of housing finance in 1988, he spent seven years running a 19-room Vermont country inn.
3_1	0.15384615384615385	But he never really left high finance -- all along he's considered it his mission to bring Wall Street innovations to low-income housing development.
3_2	1.0	Last week, Levy, having become the president of a tiny nonprofit housing organization, helped create the first real estate investment trust, or REIT, to specialize in affordable housing and community development.
3_3	1.0	REITs operate much like a mutual fund for real estate.
3_4	0.0	Through a REIT, investors own a diversified portfolio of properties and mortgages.
3_5	0.0	Levy's group, the Community Development Trust, purchases fixed-rate mortgages on homes for lower-income people and then packages the loans into securities to be resold to investors at a profit.
3_6	0.0	By creating a market for these loans, the trust makes it more attractive for lenders to make them in the first place.
3_7	0.0	``I'm loving this now,'' Levy said.
3_8	0.0	``The ability to take a market that's somewhat asleep, and be able to introduce these techniques that have worked elsewhere and adopt them, is really interesting''.
3_9	0.0	To fund its purchases, the trust last week sold $29 million in stock to such heavy hitters as the Allstate, Prudential and Metropolitan Life insurance companies; banks Citicorp and First Union; and Fannie Mae, the mortgage financing company.
3_10	0.0	The stock sale signals ``an evolutionary trend toward using more sophisticated financial strategies,'' said Kenneth Bacon, a senior vice president at Fannie Mae, which invested $4 million in the project.
3_11	0.0	``This is in many ways consistent with what you've seen happen all over the world.
3_12	0.0	In emerging markets, Latin America, Asia and Africa, people are being very innovative, and there's no reason why it can't be done here''.
3_13	0.5	Created in 1960, REITs have been used by real estate developers to finance projects from outlet malls and hotels to prisons.
3_14	0.25	REITs bought low-income housing in the past, but only to convert it to more upscale units.
3_15	0.3333333333333333	By contrast, Levy's group has pledged to only buy mortgages and buildings that primarily benefit low-income people and to maintain any property that it acquires as affordable housing.
3_16	0.4	The trust will also purchase low-income housing.
3_17	0.0	``Our REIT is going to own tons of mortgages, tons of buildings,'' said Merilyn Rovira, vice president at the Community Development Trust.
3_18	0.0	``We're going to end up with $200 million worth of assets''.
3_19	0.0	In some ways, Community Development Trust's genesis traces the evolution of community development financing.
3_20	0.0	The trust was formerly known as the Local Initiatives Managed Assets Corp.
3_21	0.0	, a non-profit group that packaged low-income mortgages into collateralized bond obligations, or securities backed by monthly mortgage payments.
3_22	0.0	LIMAC, in turn, was affiliated with Local Initiatives Support Corp.
3_23	0.0	, a nonprofit that started in 1979 by lending foundation money at below-market rates for housing and community development.
3_24	0.631578947368421	LISC ``made a lot of loans that a lot of people thought were crazy'' because they were to non-profit groups in poor neighborhoods, said Rovira, who helped structure the new real estate investment trust.
3_25	0.0	Banks, concerned about borrowers' ability to repay the loans, might shy away from making them.
3_26	0.0	But, Rovira said, ``these groups, for the most part, paid them back, interest and principal''.
3_27	0.0	LISC began to think about raising more money by packaging loans into mortgage-backed securities, a financing innovation that changed the mortgage industry by making loans much easier to get.
3_28	0.0	But LISC's loans were tiny by Wall Street standards and secured by properties scattered around the country.
3_29	0.0	And they had been originated by community organizations ranging from sophisticated to those that kept mortgage payments in a cigar box.
3_30	0.0	Enter Judd Levy.
3_31	0.0	``There's no such thing as a lack of capital for community development lending,'' Levy said last week from his Manhattan office.
3_32	0.0	``If we can securitize defaulted car loans...
3_33	0.0	then we can't say the problem in community development loans is credit risk''.
3_34	0.0	With the creation of Community Development Trust, LIMAC changed from a nonprofit organization to a for-profit REIT.
3_35	0.0	REITs don't pay taxes provided they return at least 95 percent of their taxable income to shareholders as dividends.
3_36	0.0	They tend to pay high yields of 5 percent to 10 percent, or more.
3_37	0.0	The REIT structure held several attractions for LIMAC.
3_38	0.0	The potential high yield would entice people who wouldn't otherwise invest in low-income properties.
3_39	0.1	A network of state and local housing authorities would keep the REIT supplied with mortgages.
3_40	0.0	Levy is confident the REIT is a much better investment than, say, loans to Russia and Asia that went into default over the past two years.
3_41	0.0	``You have never, ever seen a headline that such-and-such a bank took a $100 million hit on their community development portfolio,'' Levy said, ``and you never will.''
