16_0	0.6875	WASHINGTON _ While the United States is enjoying continuing prosperity, affordable housing for many of the working poor has become harder to find, a federal report said Monday.
16_1	0.32142857142857145	The report, issued by Andrew Cuomo, the U.S. secretary of housing and urban development, said that 5.4 million low-income families pay more than half their incomes for housing or live in dilapidated units, an increase of 12 percent since the economic expansion began in 1991.
16_2	0.0	The government regards housing for low-income people affordable if does not consume more than a third of a family's income.
16_3	0.5	``This is the highest need for affordable housing since we have been taking numbers,'' Cuomo said at a news conference at his department's headquarters.
16_4	0.25	Cuomo said that low-income housing was becoming less available because ``it is getting old, it is coming out of service, it is being knocked down''.
16_5	0.4444444444444444	Cuomo said that the housing difficulties for the working poor were caused by several factors, including the rising economy itself.
16_6	0.0625	In the past, building owners accepted low-income tenants whose rent was paid from their own earnings and from a government voucher program known as Section 8.
16_7	0.0	But because of the nation's rising prosperity, Cuomo said, many property owners have found that higher-income tenants have bid up the prices of the apartments beyond the poorer tenants' abilities to pay, even with the subsidies.
16_8	0.06666666666666667	Another reason, Cuomo said, was that Congress refused to approve additional Section 8 housing from 1995 through 1998, ``when we went out of the housing business''.
16_9	0.0	He blamed the Republicans in Congress for the lack of new Section 8 units, saying, ``We had proposals in the tens of thousands for every year, and Congress said zero''.
16_10	0.21428571428571427	When President Clinton asked for an additional 120,000 housing vouchers in his State of the Union message in January, Rep.
16_11	0.0	Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.
16_12	0.12	, acknowledged that no new vouchers had been approved by Congress in the four-year period, but he said that there were good reasons for that. A cause of Republican objections, he said, was a ``take one, take all'' provision that required landlords who accepted any families with housing vouchers to accept all families with them.
16_13	0.25	The Republicans' complaints were satisfied, Lazio said, and Congress approved 50,000 new housing vouchers in 1999 and 60,000 more last year.
16_14	0.0	As to Clinton's request for 120,000 more this year, Lazio said, ``I support the additional use of vouchers, but it is incumbent on us to be responsible in paying for them''.
16_15	0.0	Lazio said he had introduced a measure calling for 100,000 units, ``so we are very close''.
16_16	0.0	He said that the Clinton administration had to show where the money would come from and not resort to budget ``gimmicks'' to pay for it.
16_17	0.21052631578947367	Cuomo said that the additional 120,000 housing vouchers, which would cost $6 billion, would help ease the ``cruel irony'' of the strong economy hurting the poor by driving up rents.
16_18	0.0	``Many people are being left behind and they need help,'' he said.
16_19	0.0	When asked if his own department, which has jurisdiction over housing, should not share in the blame for the shortage, Cuomo said, ``If there was any failure, it was our failure to persuade Congress to provide funds.''
